- 1 -

(b) Notwithstanding another law to the contrary, the department shall not treat as
confidential information relating to substantiated violations of insurance claims-handling
laws when such violations:
(1) Involve failure to timely investigate, adjust, or pay claims;
(2) Involve misrepresentation of policy provisions relating to coverage;
(3) Demonstrate a pattern or practice of unfair claims settlement
practices; or
(4) Affect policyholders who are sixty-five (65) years of age or older,
residents of long-term care facilities, or otherwise classified as vulnerable adults
under the law of this state.
(c) Information subject to disclosure under subsection (b) includes:
(1) Final market conduct examination findings related to claims handling;
(2) Final administrative orders, consent orders, or settlements;
(3) Aggregated data reflecting the number and type of substantiated
consumer complaints;
(4) Corrective action plans required of insurers following substantiated
violations; and
(5) Administrative penalties or sanctions imposed for claims-handling
misconduct.
(d) Subsection (b) does not require disclosure of:
(1) Personally identifying information of any claimant or insured;
(2) Medical records or protected health information;
(3) Trade secrets, actuarial formulas, or proprietary pricing
methodologies; or
(4) Information relating to an ongoing investigation prior to a final
determination.
(e)
- 2 - 010995

(1) On and after October 1, 2026, the department shall publish the
information described in subsection (b) in a publicly accessible location and
searchable format on its website. The department shall update the information
not less than once every three (3) months.
(2)
(A) In addition to the requirement of subdivision (e)(1), by January
15, 2027, and no later than January 15 of each year thereafter, the
department shall prepare and publish in a publicly accessible location on
the department's website an annual report summarizing:
(i) The number of claims involving policyholders sixty-five
(65) years of age or older;
(ii) The number of substantiated complaints alleging failure
to adjust or pay such claims;
(iii) The insurers against whom such complaints were
substantiated; and
(iv) Enforcement actions taken as a result.
(B) The report required under subdivision (e)(2)(A) must:
(i) Not disclose personally identifying information; and
(ii) Identify insurers by name.
(f) This section does not:
(1) Waive attorney-client privilege;
(2) Require disclosure of trade secrets protected under state or federal
law; or
(3) Permit disclosure of confidential information unrelated to a
substantiated claims-handling violation.
SECTION 2. This act takes effect July 1, 2026, the public welfare requiring it.
